<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHAUNA SNOW , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 ART 
</P>
<P>
 More Met: New York's Metropolitan Museum of Art, which has rotated viewing of 
its galleries for the past three years because of budget cuts, has reopened all 
galleries to the public on a full-time basis. The reopenings were made possible 
through the Cultural Challenge Initiative, a city-state program that has 
earmarked a total of $10 million for cultural institutions, including $421,000 
for the Met reopenings. Cantor Fitzgerald, a New York financial holding 
company, has provided an additional $421,000 in matching funds. The change 
comes at the start of the holiday season, traditionally the period of greatest 
museum attendance. Most galleries have been closed for half the day -- rotating 
mornings and afternoons -- since 1991, after the Met suffered a $3.5 million 
cut in city support. TELEVISION 
</P>
<P>
 Congresswoman Sugarbaker: It hasn't been promoted as such, but Linda 
Bloodworth-Thomason's midseason series for CBS is a sort of sequel to her 
former hit "Designing Women," with Delta Burke returning as ex-beauty queen 
Suzanne Sugarbaker. The premise of "Women of the House" is that Sugarbaker 
takes over her late husband's seat in the U.S. House of Representatives; Teri 
Garr, Valerie Mahaffey and Patricia Heaton co-star as aides. A premiere date 
has not yet been set. MOVIES 
</P>
<P>
 'Free Willy' News: Film companies Warner Bros. and New Regency Productions 
have announced plans to donate $2 million to a new foundation to help Keiko, 
the captive whale who starred in the movie "Free Willy," which earned the 
studios $100 million. Keiko has been a huge public relations problem for the 
filmmakers ever since it was discovered that instead of swimming to freedom, as 
he does in the film, Keiko lives trapped in a too-small tank in Mexico, losing 
weight and suffering from a herpes-like skin disease. Several other efforts 
have been launched to help Keiko, but the Humane Society of the United States 
on Wednesday called the Warner/New Regency donations "the most hopeful 
opportunity to fulfill countless people's desire to 'Free Willy.' " In 
announcing its gift, Warner, the movie's distributor, made a point of noting 
its past assistance in purifying and cooling the water in Keiko's tank. Warner 
clearly hopes to put the controversy behind it by next summer when outtakes of 
Keiko from the first film will be used in a sequel, "Free Willy II: The Return 
Home." 
</P>
<P>
 The Falcon's Ransom: The Maltese Falcon, one of Hollywood's most famous film 
props, could fetch up to $50,000 when put up for sale next month, Christie's 
auction house said Thursday. The lead statue, center of the classic detective 
film that established Humphrey Bogart as a major star, will be sold in New York 
on Dec. 6. The falcon was left by studio boss Jack Warner to 
actor-director-producer William Conrad as a gesture of appreciation. Conrad 
died earlier this year. A second Maltese Falcon statuette -- made of resin and 
believed to have been held by Bogart in publicity shots for the movie -- was 
scheduled to be auctioned by Christie's in June, 1993, but the auction house 
declined to sell the falcon when it could not be proved that the statuette was 
used in the 1941 movie. POP/ROCK 
</P>
<P>
 Making Change: The music industry's AIDS organization, LIFEbeat, kicks off its 
third annual fund-raiser, "Counter AID -- It's About Change," on Dec. 1, World 
AIDS Day. The week-long effort urges music patrons to round off their purchases 
to the nearest dollar, with the extra money donated to LIFEbeat to help those 
living with HIV and AIDS. As part of the effort, well-known musicians and 
celebrities will man the cash registers of more than 200 record stores 
nationwide on Dec. 3 from noon to 4 p.m. Those scheduled to appear locally 
include Concrete Blonde's Johnette Napolitano, Motley Crue's Tommy Lee, 4 Non 
Blonde's Linda Perry and Me'Shell NdegeOcello at Tower Records, Sunset; L.A. 
Laker Cedric Ceballos, Coolio, Shai and "In Living Color's" Jamie Foxx at Tower 
Records, Sherman Oaks; Aaliyah, Immature and "Married . . . With Children" star 
Katey Sagal at Sam Goody, Universal City Walk; and Joe Penny and the band White 
Zombie at the Hard Rock Cafe, Beverly Center. QUICK TAKES 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles radio station KLSX-FM (97.1) will broadcast Westwood One's radio 
simulcast of "Hoodoo U Voodoo," the Rolling Stones live pay-per-view concert 
from Miami's Joe Robbie Stadium tonight. The show begins at 6 p.m. . . . 
Doctors for David Crosby, 53, who underwent a liver transplant at UCLA Medical 
Center Sunday and was moved out of intensive care on Wednesday, say the singer 
could be out of the hospital in two weeks. SHAUNA SNOW 
</P>
