</P>
<P>
 "I think parents calling the school about their children would add to the 
confusion." 
</P>
<P>
 Hien Nguyen, 15, junior, Fountain Valley 
</P>
<P>
 "The biggest problem would be the panic of everyone." 
</P>
<P>
 Ann Amigable, 14, freshman, Rosary 
</P>
<P>
 "The top (floor). We'll have to jump . . . and panic might be a problem." 
</P>
<P>
 Dawn Hyepock, 15, sophomore, Westminster 
</P>
<P>
 "The rebuilding process (that) the school and students would have to go 
through." 
</P>
<P>
 Bach Vu, 17, senior, Santiago 
</P>
<P>
 "Since we're on a hill, there would be no way to communicate if all the power 
lines were shut down." 
</P>
<P>
 Veena Lucas, 16, junior, Brea Olinda 
</P>
<P>
 "People panicking. Even though they're supposed to go under their desks, 
students would want to get out of the classroom as quickly as possible, 
especially if they are sitting near a glass window." 
</P>
<P>
 Derek Stucker, 16, junior, Irvine 
</P>
<P>
 "Having to come down from upstairs. If the stairs are gone, there would be 
nothing to help people down to escape." 
</P>
<P>
 Nathan Vanderburg, 16, junior, Katella 
</P>
<P>
 "The safe evacuation of all students out of the building." 
</P>
<P>
 Sharon Yee, 16, junior, Huntington Beach 
</P>
<P>
 "People freaking out." 
</P>
<P>
 Rigo Hernandez, 16, junior, Laguna Beach 
</P>
